results.name: Number of non-commutative rings with 1 containing n elements.
comment: We consider rings in which multiplication is associative and has a unit, but where there is at least one pair of non-commuting elements.
link: C. Noebauer, Home page [Archived copy as of 2008 from web.archive.org]
example: a(n)=0 for n<=7 and a(8)=1, so all rings (with unit) of cardinality at most 7 are commutative, while the smallest non-commutative ring (with unit) has cardinality 8 and is unique up to isomorphism; it can be represented as the ring of upper-triangular matrices of size 2 over F_2.
results.author: Hugues Randriam (randriam(AT)enst.fr), Jan 24 2007, Jan 29 2007
